      <hedline>
        <hl1>Bush in Europe: An Uneasy Alliance</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Albert Liebman calls for serious debate in Congress on issues that have have split America's European allies: Pres Bush's opposition to Kyoto Protocol and his intention of proceeding unilaterally with missile defense system</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Deep U.S.-Europe Split Casts Long Shadow on Bush Tour'' (news article, June 15):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Deep U.S.-Europe Split Casts Long Shadow on Bush Tour'' (news article, June 15):</p>
        <p>During his European trip, President Bush has enunciated his opposition to the Kyoto Protocol and his intention of proceeding unilaterally with a missile defense system. This has produced a split with our European allies and, if these policies are pursued, will mark a deviation from some 50 years of fruitful collaboration that has largely produced peace and considerable prosperity for Europe and the United States.</p>
        <p>The consequences of the president's policies are unpredictable and perhaps ominous. We now need serious debate in our Congress on these vital issues. And we must be careful that the mantra of ''bipartisanship'' is not used to throttle necessary debate.</p>
        <p>ALBERT LIEBMAN  Mequon, Wis., June 15, 2001</p>
      </block>
